  "prompt": "What is the difference between fact and theory in science jargon?",
  "response": "In scientific terminology:\n\nA \"fact\" is an observed, verifiable piece of empirical evidence that can be directly measured or experienced. It's something that has been confirmed through repeated observation or measurement.\n\nA \"theory\" is a well-substantiated explanation of some aspect of the natural world based on a large body of knowledge that has been repeatedly confirmed through observation and experimentation. Contrary to popular usage, a scientific theory is not a guess or speculation, but a comprehensive explanatory framework that can make predictions and has been rigorously tested.\n\nKey differences:\n- Facts are specific observations\n- Theories are broader explanatory systems that integrate multiple facts\n- Theories can be modified or refined as new evidence emerges\n- Theories explain how and why something happens, while facts describe what happened\n\nExamples:\n- Fact: Gravity causes objects to fall toward the Earth's center\n- Theory: Theory of Gravity explains how and why gravitational attraction occurs between objects\n\nA scientific theory is the highest level of scientific understanding, not a mere speculation as the term is often misused in everyday language.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
